<br>
Thanks for the very good info..<br>
<br>
Anyway back to the rant not aimed at prathun at all....<br>
<br>
The disaster that was ... ldon raids...<br>
<br>
Ok lets try and sum up the mass fun ldon raids were....<br>
<br>
1. limit 36 people. This content came out when time was still the main target of the high end guilds.. time used 72 people and unless you'd been farming it a few months you needed 60   Ldon raid halved that number meaning people were excluded. If people had to log... guess what? they were screwing the guild over.<br>
 <br>
2. Locked &quot;expedition&quot; The second the accept mission was taken the 36 people in the adventure were locked and no one could be added or dropped. This meant that people that were ld when you started the raid were left out. At the time it was rare for at least one person in the raid to not be ld in butcher etc.<br>
<br>
3. Time limits - all the raids had timers clearly on the window... others had timers no one knew about until you suddenly failed as well . No hints at all really about the time you needed to complete sub sections without trial and error or dev/off server info.<br>
<br>
4. death limit! yes enough people die and you fail.. combine this with lots of ambushes and triggered bosses and unmezzable hoards on zone in and literally you could fail a raid the first minute you zoned in. people were SCARED to die.<br>
<br>
5. INSANE lockout times. if you started an ldon raid, regardless if you bothered to zone in or even won it, you had a 6 ish (I'm slowly forgetting the details thank god - pun intended) day lock out period. tack on another day because you had to start the raid later and later if for some reason wanted to farm it. Combine that with the other points and you get an idea on the fun?<br>
<br>
6. Puzzle games in ldon!!! Each zone had a specific riddle/order/way of dealing with mobs. this ties in with the hidden timers but things like the ruj gobos that ran and collected 10 friends to never ending ice gobos until you killed some boss mob you never really knew about without the fd flopping monks. Each zone was to be learned from trial and error trying to figure out the fun tricks from the just plain number 7's (see 7 =p) combine that with the death rate fail AND the lockout and oooooooooo.<br>
<br>
7. bugs and more bugs. ldon raids were the buggiest crap I've even seen soe put out pre uqua. Fun things like boss mobs you need to kill in orders unknown to trigger x y then z and a twist of lemon in some Byzantine mousetrap that only a gnome could have created. BUT NOOOOO that's not all!!! you might have done x y z right but the zone bugged and the script crashed on the twist of lemon!!!! how were the players to know???? who cared after 2 tries other than kinu???????????<br>
<br>
8. screwed up mobs.. name it, unmezzable, insane mr, un snarable un lullable un this un that hard hitting trash mobs that were packed into the same single group zones you know and prolly don;t love. Pulling was bad enough but a misspull = death = fail mission = lockout = pissed off guild  members that decided that was the last ldon they'd log on for.<br>
<br>
9. unforgiving basic difficulty. Ok so say your guild just took the month to learn one of the ldon raids from time level. You know need your best geared time level tanks and healers etc. none of these raids were viable with new members with poor resists and the people most time geared generally were the first to forget to log on ldon nights.<br>
<br>
10. Poor zone construction... ok you've seen guk right? or the caves in mistmoore? imagine trying to fit 36 people into those? Get the fun image? now keep it for 4 hours.<br>
<br>
11. very poor reward. So what was the end result to jumping though all these night ending hoops of flaming crap content? things like   mana augs and spell shield 4% and only a few of them at the very very end. There were a few good ones like the healing focus aug but to rely on them was a folly. All in all reward vs risk wasn;t even on par with even the first 2 phases of time.<br>
<br>
<br>
Ldon raids were the start of the road to summit for soe. the high end guilds were not impressed with ldon at all and their members dropped like flies. When gates came out, uqua put the nail in it but by no means was that the only thing.<br>
<br>
Only thing I could liken ldon raids to was plane of sky at level 50. I mean that zone was meant for 55 60, not 50 and man the rewards blew lol.<br>
<br>
I see much promise in inkua (ok whatever the freakin name is) in that you have a balanced zone that is *gasp* FUN (omg wtf?), creative and has decent loot to boot. That combined with the summit and increased responsiveness of soe shows more hope then any since pre pop imo.<br>
<br>
In relation to the original post... amen... pave over that crap and make it suitable for casual guilds. Seed it with decent equipment for the targeted groups so they are worth doing.<br>
<br>
Cheers!<br>
-Liq<br>
